[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Chapter 7 Preface — Predicting What Happens Next
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every healthcare organization has the same fantasy: what if we could see the future? Not in a crystal ball sense, but in a "this patient is about to get much sicker and we could do something about it right now" sense. Predictive analytics is the closest we've gotten to making that real. And the frustrating part? The math has been good enough for years. The hard part was never the algorithms. It was everything else.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let me be specific about what I mean. Logistic regression has been around since the 1950s. Decision trees since the 1960s. The LACE index for readmission risk was published in 2010. The Charlson Comorbidity Index dates to 1987. Healthcare has been scoring risk for decades. So why does it still feel like most organizations are flying blind?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Because building a model is maybe 20% of the problem. The other 80% is: getting clean data, integrating the score into a workflow someone actually uses, making sure the model doesn't quietly become racist, convincing clinicians to trust a number, and figuring out what to actually *do* when the model says "this patient is high risk." A risk score without an intervention pathway is just an expensive anxiety generator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## What Predictive Analytics Actually Means in Healthcare
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's be precise about terminology, because "predictive analytics" gets thrown around loosely enough to be meaningless.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In this chapter, we're talking about **supervised learning models that estimate the probability of a future event for a specific patient or population**. The event might be a hospital readmission, an ED visit, a missed appointment, disease progression, or mortality. The output is typically a probability (0 to 1) or a risk tier (low/medium/high). The input is whatever structured data you can assemble about the patient: demographics, diagnoses, procedures, medications, utilization history, lab values, and sometimes social determinants.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is distinct from anomaly detection (Chapter 3), which finds unusual patterns without predicting a specific outcome. It's distinct from time series forecasting (Chapter 12), which predicts aggregate volumes rather than individual patient events. And it's distinct from reinforcement learning (Chapter 15), which optimizes sequential decisions rather than making point-in-time predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The core question in predictive analytics is always: **given what we know about this patient right now, what is the probability that X will happen in the next Y days?**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Algorithmic Landscape
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Healthcare risk prediction draws from a surprisingly small toolkit of algorithms. Here's the honest breakdown of what actually gets used in production (as opposed to what gets published in journals):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Logistic Regression
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Still the workhorse. Seriously. For binary outcomes (readmitted vs. not, no-show vs. showed up), logistic regression is interpretable, fast to train, easy to validate, and performs within a few percentage points of more complex models on most healthcare prediction tasks. When a clinician asks "why did this patient get flagged?", you can point to specific coefficients. That matters more than you'd think.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Gradient Boosted Trees (XGBoost, LightGBM)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The go-to when you need better discrimination and can sacrifice some interpretability. Gradient boosting handles mixed data types well (categorical diagnoses alongside continuous lab values), captures non-linear relationships, and handles missing data gracefully. Most production healthcare risk models built in the last five years use some variant of gradient boosting. The tradeoff is that explaining individual predictions requires additional tooling (SHAP values, partial dependence plots).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Random Forests
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Less common in production than you'd expect from the literature, but still useful for ensemble approaches and as a baseline. They're harder to overfit than single trees and provide built-in feature importance, but they tend to underperform gradient boosting on tabular healthcare data.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Neural Networks (Deep Learning)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Surprisingly rare in production healthcare risk scoring, despite dominating the research literature. The reasons are practical: tabular healthcare data (which is what most risk models consume) doesn't benefit much from deep learning over gradient boosting. Neural networks shine when you have sequential data (clinical notes over time, medication sequences) or very high-dimensional inputs. But for "predict readmission from 50 structured features," XGBoost usually wins on both accuracy and interpretability.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Survival Analysis (Cox Proportional Hazards, Accelerated Failure Time)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Underappreciated in healthcare ML. When your question is "when will this happen?" rather than "will this happen in 30 days?", survival models are the right tool. They handle censored data naturally (patients who haven't had the event yet aren't failures; they just haven't been observed long enough). Disease progression modeling and time-to-event predictions benefit enormously from survival analysis frameworks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Honest Truth About Model Selection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what nobody tells you in the ML courses: for most healthcare prediction tasks with structured data, the difference between a well-tuned logistic regression and a well-tuned XGBoost model is maybe 2-4 AUC points. The difference between either of those and a model trained on bad data, or deployed without proper calibration, or built on a biased training population, is 15-20 AUC points. Feature engineering and data quality matter far more than algorithm selection. Every time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Is Genuinely Hard
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Calibration Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Discrimination (can the model rank patients by risk?) and calibration (are the predicted probabilities accurate?) are different things. A model can have excellent discrimination (AUC of 0.85) while being terribly calibrated (predicting 40% risk for patients who actually have 15% risk). In healthcare, calibration matters enormously because it drives resource allocation. If your model says 500 patients have >50% readmission risk, you need enough care managers to call all 500. If the true rate is 20%, you've massively over-allocated resources. Calibration is harder than discrimination, degrades faster over time, and gets almost no attention in most ML tutorials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Fairness Minefield
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Risk scores in healthcare have a documented history of encoding racial and socioeconomic disparities. The most famous example: a widely-used commercial algorithm for identifying patients who need extra care was shown to systematically underestimate the health needs of Black patients, because it used healthcare spending as a proxy for health needs. Spending reflects access, not need. Patients who face barriers to care spend less, so the model concluded they were healthier. This wasn't a bug in the algorithm; it was a bug in the problem formulation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every risk model you build needs to be evaluated for fairness across demographic subgroups. Not as an afterthought. As a core requirement. This means: equal calibration across groups, equal false positive/negative rates, and careful examination of what your features are actually measuring versus what you think they're measuring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Temporal Drift Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Healthcare changes. Coding practices shift. New treatments alter disease trajectories. Pandemics reshape utilization patterns. A model trained on 2019 data performed terribly in 2020 (for obvious reasons) and didn't fully recover in 2021-2022 because patient behavior had permanently shifted. Models need monitoring, retraining schedules, and drift detection. A model that was excellent at deployment can become actively harmful within 12-18 months if nobody's watching.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The "So What?" Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the one that kills most predictive analytics initiatives. You build a beautiful model. It accurately identifies high-risk patients. You deploy it. And then... nothing happens. Because nobody built the intervention workflow. Nobody staffed the care management team to handle the volume. Nobody integrated the score into the EHR where clinicians actually work. The model becomes a dashboard that leadership looks at quarterly and nobody acts on daily.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The recipes in this chapter all include intervention pathway design, not just model architecture. A prediction without an action is just surveillance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## How the Recipes Progress
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This chapter moves from simple, well-understood prediction problems to increasingly complex ones. The progression isn't just about algorithmic sophistication; it's about the difficulty of the surrounding system: data requirements, intervention design, ethical considerations, and operational integration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipes 7.1-7.2 (Simple):** Binary outcomes with clear ground truth, abundant training data, and low-stakes interventions. Appointment no-shows and propensity-to-pay are great starting points because you can iterate quickly, measure impact easily, and the consequences of model errors are manageable. These are where you build organizational muscle for predictive analytics.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipes 7.3-7.5 (Simple to Medium):** Still well-defined outcomes, but the intervention pathways get more complex and the data requirements expand. Patient churn prediction requires inferring intent from behavior. ED visit prediction involves social determinants that aren't in your EHR. Readmission risk is a well-studied problem with regulatory implications (CMS penalties) that raises the stakes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipes 7.6-7.7 (Medium to Complex):** The shift from "who is high risk?" to "who is *becoming* high risk?" Rising risk identification requires longitudinal modeling and rate-of-change calculations. Length of stay prediction must update dynamically as a hospitalization progresses. These recipes introduce the concept of models that evolve their predictions over time rather than making a single point-in-time score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Recipes 7.8-7.10 (Complex):** The hardest problems in healthcare prediction. Disease progression modeling operates over multi-year time horizons with treatment effects confounding the signal. ICU mortality scoring is the highest-stakes prediction in medicine, with profound ethical implications. Optimal intervention timing pushes into causal inference territory, predicting not just *who* but *when* to act for maximum benefit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## What You'll Need
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Most recipes in this chapter assume you have:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Structured patient data** in a queryable format (claims, EHR extracts, ADT feeds)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Historical outcomes** for training (at least 12-18 months of labeled data for most use cases)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **A feature engineering pipeline** that can assemble patient-level feature vectors from raw data
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Model serving infrastructure** that can score patients in batch or near-real-time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **An intervention workflow** that consumes risk scores and triggers actions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m If you don't have the intervention workflow, start there. Seriously. The fanciest model in the world is worthless if nobody acts on its output.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## A Note on Regulation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Risk scoring in healthcare touches several regulatory domains. CMS uses specific risk models (HCC risk adjustment) for payment. Quality measures (like the Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program) create financial incentives around specific predictions. State laws may restrict how predictive models can be used in coverage decisions. And the FDA has started asserting jurisdiction over clinical decision support software that uses ML.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m None of this should stop you from building. But it should inform your design. Every recipe notes where regulatory considerations apply, and the more complex recipes (particularly 7.8 and 7.9) include specific guidance on validation requirements for clinical-grade predictions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's start with the simplest, most immediately valuable prediction problem in healthcare operations: which patients aren't going to show up for their appointments.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *→ [Recipe 7.1 — Appointment No-Show Prediction](chapter07.01-appointment-no-show-prediction)*
